descript.abstract: Elevation grid of the state of Florida derived from 30-meter (1 arc-second) National Elevation Dataset (NED) data which was then resampled down to 90 meters and converted to integer cell values. This data is designed to support U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) disaster preparedness efforts and is meant to be used at a broad scale and for informational purposes only.

procstep.procdesc: The NED data was derived from the original 1:24,000-scale USGS topographic map bare-earth contours, which were converted into gridded quadrangle-based DEM tiles at a constant post spacing (grid cell size) of either 30 meters (circa pre-1990s data) or 10 meters (circa 1990s and later data). These individual-quadrangle DEMs were then converted to spherical coordinates (latitude/longitude decimal degrees) and edge-matched to ensure seamlessness. The NED source data for this dataset consists of a mixture of 30-meter- and 10-meter-resolution DEMs.
The NED data was downloaded from http://seamless.usgs.gov circa 2004 or 2005. This data was then projected into UTM Zone 17 NAD83 at 30-meter horizontal resolution.
The 30-meter UTM elevation grid was resampled to 90-meter resolution and Zvalues were rounded to whole integers.
